    About the Company

    L’Oréal manufactures and sells cosmetic products for women and men worldwide. It offers skincare and haircare products, deodorants, make-up products, perfumes, oral cosmetics, hair colors, styling and shaping products, nail care products, and dermocosmetics.

    The company provides its products under the Lancôme, Giorgio Armani, Yves Saint Laurent

    Beauté, Biotherm, Kiehl’s, Ralph Lauren, Shu Uemura, Cacharel, Helena Rubinstein, Clarisonic, Diesel, Viktor&Rolf, Yue Sai, Maison Martin Margiela, Urban Decay, Guy Laroche, Paloma Picasso, Vichy, La Roche-Posay, SkinCeuticals, Roger&Gallet, Sanoflore, L’Oréal Paris, Garnier, Maybelline New York, Softsheen.Carson, Essie, L’Oréal Professionnel, Kérastase, Redken, Matrix, Pureology, Shu Uemura Art of Hair, Mizani, Essie, CARITA, and Decleor brand names.

    Growth Insight

    updated Apr 27, 2025

    Growing
    L'Oreal acquired Gowoonsesang Cosmetics, including the South Korean skincare brand Dr.G, from Swiss retailer Migros, marking a significant expansion in the Korean dermocosmetics market. The company completed a record 18 M&A deals worth KRW2.3 trillion in 2024, driven by the growing popularity of Korean cosmetics in the US market. L'Oreal UK's pre-tax profit increased from £220m to £248.3m in 2024, reflecting operational excellence and cost management. Additionally, L'Oreal UK's sales turnover reached £1.55bn in 2024, up from £1.43bn in 2023, marking a significant increase in revenue attributed to market performance and operational excellence. L'Oreal reported a 3.5% rise in like-for-like first-quarter sales, reaching 11.7 billion euros, driven by strong demand in Europe despite challenges in the U.S. market. The company experienced better-than-expected performance in China, contributing to its overall sales growth.

    Research and Development Insight

    L'Oréal is researching compositions involving isolated probiotic bacterial strains and their actives, as described in 'Probiotic bacteria composition for inhibiting fungal proliferation.' The company is also developing methods and compositions for skin improvement, including a composition containing a supernatant from bacterial fermentation with at least three metabolites, as detailed in 'New composition for treatment of skin conditions.' These efforts focus on skin health and microbial-based cosmetic solutions.

    Products and Services

    This information is generated using AI and may include errors or omissions.Learn more.
    Product Name  
    Product Description  
    Consumer ProductsL'Oréal offers a range of consumer beauty products including brands like L'Oréal Paris, Maybelline New York, Garnier, NYX Professional Makeup, and Mixa, available in various retail channels.
    Professional ProductsL'Oréal provides professional haircare products through brands such as L'Oréal Professionnel, Kérastase, MATRIX, Biolage, and Redken, catering to salons and professional stylists.
    Luxury ProductsL'Oréal's luxury division includes high-end beauty brands like Lancôme, Yves Saint Laurent, Giorgio Armani, Biotherm, Kiehl's, Valentino, and Prada, offering premium cosmetics and fragrances.
    Active CosmeticsL'Oréal's active cosmetics division features dermatological skincare brands like Vichy, La Roche-Posay, and CeraVe, focusing on health-oriented skincare solutions.
    EpiskinL'Oréal develops reconstructed human skin models for non-animal testing of cosmetic products, available for use by other companies and organizations.
    L'Oréal Fund for Nature RegenerationA €50 million fund aimed at supporting projects that restore damaged ecosystems, including forests, mangroves, and marine areas.
